{"title_page": "Tarik Freitekh", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Tarik Freitekh\n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642 \u0641\u0631\u064a\u062a\u062e\n| native_name_lang   = Arabic\n| image              = Attachment 180115032013.jpg\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1987|10|5|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = Jerusalem, Israel\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| residence          = California, United States\n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Businessman, producer, director\n| organization       = Petronor Oil\n}}\n'''Tarik Freitekh''' {{lang-ar|\u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642 \u0641\u0631\u064a\u062a\u062e}}<ref>https://www.elfann.com/news/show/1234095/%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B5%D9%88%D8%B1--%D8%B7%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%82-%D9%81%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%AA%D8%AE-%D9%8A%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%8A-%D9%86%D9%85%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%8B-%D9%85%D9%86%D8%B2%D9%84%D9%87-%D9%88%D8%AD%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%B3%D9%87-%D9%8A%D9%82%D9%81-%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%84</ref>; born 5 October 1987) is an American, businessman, producer, and director.\nHe runs his own international distribution company in [[Dubai]], recording studios in [[Hollywood, California]], and video studios in [[Miami, Florida]]. He is the co-founder of Petronor Oil, CBDPH,<ref>https://www.openthenews.com/kourtney-kardashianaes-launches-anti-aging-cbd-from-billionaire-tarik-freitekhaes-largest-cbd-farms/</ref><ref>https://timesofcbd.com/kourtney-kardashian-goes-to-mask-cbd-beauty-mask-debut-by-tarik-freitekhs-farms/ </ref> Starbuzz Entertainment, and World Music production.<ref>https://arabic.rt.com/news/771567-\u0641\u0631\u064a\u062a\u062e-\u0641\u0646\u064a-\u0647\u064a\u0641\u0627\u0621-\u0643\u0627\u0631\u062f\u0627\u0634\u064a\u0627\u0646/ </ref><ref>https://english.alarabiya.net/en/life-style/entertainment/2014/08/22/Haifa-Wehbe-takes-up-ice-bucket-challenge</ref>\n<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WCFhTDinTcc</ref>\n<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O00Cfti-A6Q&t=103s</ref>\n<ref>https://www.albawaba.com/entertainment/international-director-tarek-freitekh-and-justin-bieber-make-you-\u201cwork-it\u201d-615303</ref>\n<ref>http://forbes.financial/bitcoin_past_issues_tarik_freitekh_2018/</ref>\n<ref>https://arabic.rt.com/news/780112-\u0647\u064a\u0641\u0627\u0621-\u0648\u0647\u0628\u064a-\u0623\u0643\u062b\u0631-\u062c\u0631\u0623\u0629-\u0641\u064a-breathing-you-in/</ref>\n==Career==\nFreitekh's music label signed the Arab diva [[Haifa Wehbe]], one of the Middle East's most famous singers and actresses.<ref name=three>{{cite news\n|url=http://chababs.com/\u0645\u0648\u0633\u064a\u0642\u0649/15077/\u0647\u064a\u0641\u0627\u0621-\u0648\u0647\u0628\u064a-\u0641\u064a-\u0639\u0645\u0644-\u0645\u0646-\u0627\u0644\u0639\u064a\u0627\u0631-\u0627\u0644\u062b\u0642\u064a\u0644-\u0645\u0639-\u0627\u0644\u0645\u062e\u0631\u062c-\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0644\u0645\u064a-\u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642-\u0641\u0631\u064a\u062a\u062e\n|accessdate=2014-05-28\n|title=Haifa Wehbe works with \"high-caliber\" global director Tareq Freitekh\n|newspaper=Chabab\n|date=February 5, 2014\n|language=Arabic\n}}</ref> Also, in 2014, the Cuban singer [[Nayer]] signed with his label; she is known for her hit songs with [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]] (\"Pearly Gates\", \"Sauvamente\") and [[Ne-Yo]] (\"Give Me Everything\"). He recently finished directing a music video for the rap artist [[Snoop Dogg]] plus previous projects with [[Shakira]], [[Shaggy (musician)|Shaggy]], [[R. Kelly]], [[Tamer Hosny]], and [[Jennifer Lopez]].<ref name=four>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.lebanonfiles.com/news/635841\n|accessdate=2014-05-27\n|title=Tariq Freitekh combines Akon Jennifer Lopez\n|newspaper=Lebanon Files\n|date=November 29, 2013\n|language=Arabic\n}}</ref>\nFreitekh also received the award for best director at the Los Angeles Festival of Music for the song \"Cherokee\" in 2012.<ref name=five>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.masress.com/elsaba7/65481\n|accessdate=2014-05-27\n|title=Global Director Tarik Freitekh Discovers Talented International Singers\n|newspaper=Masress\n|date=January 1, 2013\n|language=Arabic\n}}</ref><ref name=six>{{cite news\n |url         = http://la.lifediverse.com/tarik-freitekh-wins-best-director-at-music-video-film-festival/\n |accessdate  = 2014-05-27\n |title       = Tarik Freitekh Wins Best Director at Music Video Film Festival\n |newspaper   = LA Life Magazine\n |date        = August 10, 2012\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140528045720/http://la.lifediverse.com/tarik-freitekh-wins-best-director-at-music-video-film-festival/\n |archivedate = May 28, 2014\n}}</ref>\n==Personal life==\nFreitekh owns a number of real estate in [[Dubai]], Europe, and the US, including a three-floor mansion in Hollywood Hills sold to him for $7 million and a penthouse in [[Miami]], bought for $2.3 million in 2012. In December 2017, Freitekh was honored as a goodwill ambassador by the [[United Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/rahejaweb/goodwill-ambassador-is-a-person-who-advocate-2y1pw|title=Goodwill Ambassador|website=Buzzfeed.com|access-date=18 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://goknews.com/goodwill-ambassador/|title=Goodwill Ambassador - Gok News|date=12 December 2017|website=GokNews.com|access-date=18 December 2017}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Freitekh, Tarik}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Technology Sydney alumni]]\n[[Category:American people of Palestinian descent]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Tarik Freitekh|timestamp=20200408090742|year=2020|month=April|day=8|substed=yes}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Tarik Freitekh|date=8 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Tarik Freitekh\n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642 \u0641\u0631\u064a\u062a\u062e\n| native_name_lang   = Arabic\n| image              = Attachment 180115032013.jpg\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1987|10|5|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = Jerusalem, Israel\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| residence          = California, United States\n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Businessman, producer, director\n| organization       = Petronor Oil\n}}\n\n'''Tarik Freitekh''' {{lang-ar|\u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642 \u0641\u0631\u064a\u062a\u062e}}<ref>https://www.elfann.com/news/show/1234095/%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B5%D9%88%D8%B1--%D8%B7%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%82-%D9%81%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%AA%D8%AE-%D9%8A%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%8A-%D9%86%D9%85%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%8B-%D9%85%D9%86%D8%B2%D9%84%D9%87-%D9%88%D8%AD%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%B3%D9%87-%D9%8A%D9%82%D9%81-%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%84</ref>; born 5 October 1987) is an American, businessman, producer, and director.\nHe runs his own international distribution company in [[Dubai]], recording studios in [[Hollywood, California]], and video studios in [[Miami, Florida]]. He is the co-founder of Petronor Oil, CBDPH,<ref>https://www.openthenews.com/kourtney-kardashianaes-launches-anti-aging-cbd-from-billionaire-tarik-freitekhaes-largest-cbd-farms/</ref><ref>https://timesofcbd.com/kourtney-kardashian-goes-to-mask-cbd-beauty-mask-debut-by-tarik-freitekhs-farms/ </ref> Starbuzz Entertainment, and World Music production.<ref>https://arabic.rt.com/news/771567-\u0641\u0631\u064a\u062a\u062e-\u0641\u0646\u064a-\u0647\u064a\u0641\u0627\u0621-\u0643\u0627\u0631\u062f\u0627\u0634\u064a\u0627\u0646/ </ref><ref>https://english.alarabiya.net/en/life-style/entertainment/2014/08/22/Haifa-Wehbe-takes-up-ice-bucket-challenge</ref>\n<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WCFhTDinTcc</ref>\n<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O00Cfti-A6Q&t=103s</ref>\n<ref>https://www.albawaba.com/entertainment/international-director-tarek-freitekh-and-justin-bieber-make-you-\u201cwork-it\u201d-615303</ref>\n<ref>http://forbes.financial/bitcoin_past_issues_tarik_freitekh_2018/</ref>\n<ref>https://arabic.rt.com/news/780112-\u0647\u064a\u0641\u0627\u0621-\u0648\u0647\u0628\u064a-\u0623\u0643\u062b\u0631-\u062c\u0631\u0623\u0629-\u0641\u064a-breathing-you-in/</ref>\n\n==Career==\nFreitekh's music label signed the Arab diva [[Haifa Wehbe]], one of the Middle East's most famous singers and actresses.<ref name=three>{{cite news\n\n|url=http://chababs.com/\u0645\u0648\u0633\u064a\u0642\u0649/15077/\u0647\u064a\u0641\u0627\u0621-\u0648\u0647\u0628\u064a-\u0641\u064a-\u0639\u0645\u0644-\u0645\u0646-\u0627\u0644\u0639\u064a\u0627\u0631-\u0627\u0644\u062b\u0642\u064a\u0644-\u0645\u0639-\u0627\u0644\u0645\u062e\u0631\u062c-\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0644\u0645\u064a-\u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642-\u0641\u0631\u064a\u062a\u062e\n\n|accessdate=2014-05-28\n|title=Haifa Wehbe works with \"high-caliber\" global director Tareq Freitekh\n|newspaper=Chabab\n|date=February 5, 2014\n|language=Arabic\n}}</ref> Also, in 2014, the Cuban singer [[Nayer]] signed with his label; she is known for her hit songs with [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]] (\"Pearly Gates\", \"Sauvamente\") and [[Ne-Yo]] (\"Give Me Everything\"). He recently finished directing a music video for the rap artist [[Snoop Dogg]] plus previous projects with [[Shakira]], [[Shaggy (musician)|Shaggy]], [[R. Kelly]], [[Tamer Hosny]], and [[Jennifer Lopez]].<ref name=four>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.lebanonfiles.com/news/635841\n|accessdate=2014-05-27\n|title=Tariq Freitekh combines Akon Jennifer Lopez\n|newspaper=Lebanon Files\n|date=November 29, 2013\n|language=Arabic\n}}</ref>\nFreitekh also received the award for best director at the Los Angeles Festival of Music for the song \"Cherokee\" in 2012.<ref name=five>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.masress.com/elsaba7/65481\n\n|accessdate=2014-05-27\n|title=Global Director Tarik Freitekh Discovers Talented International Singers\n|newspaper=Masress\n|date=January 1, 2013\n|language=Arabic\n}}</ref><ref name=six>{{cite news\n |url         = http://la.lifediverse.com/tarik-freitekh-wins-best-director-at-music-video-film-festival/\n |accessdate  = 2014-05-27\n |title       = Tarik Freitekh Wins Best Director at Music Video Film Festival\n |newspaper   = LA Life Magazine\n |date        = August 10, 2012\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140528045720/http://la.lifediverse.com/tarik-freitekh-wins-best-director-at-music-video-film-festival/\n |archivedate = May 28, 2014\n}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFreitekh owns a number of real estate in [[Dubai]], Europe, and the US, including a three-floor mansion in Hollywood Hills sold to him for $7 million and a penthouse in [[Miami]], bought for $2.3 million in 2012. In December 2017, Freitekh was honored as a goodwill ambassador by the [[United Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/rahejaweb/goodwill-ambassador-is-a-person-who-advocate-2y1pw|title=Goodwill Ambassador|website=Buzzfeed.com|access-date=18 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://goknews.com/goodwill-ambassador/|title=Goodwill Ambassador - Gok News|date=12 December 2017|website=GokNews.com|access-date=18 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Freitekh, Tarik}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Technology Sydney alumni]]\n[[Category:American people of Palestinian descent]]\n", "name_user": "Bardia EsmaeilZadeh", "label": "safe", "comment": "Err Solve", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tarik_Freitekh"}
{"title_page": "West Trenton Line (NJ Transit)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{about|the proposed New Jersey Transit line|the SEPTA Regional Rail line|West Trenton Line (SEPTA)}}\n{{West Trenton Line Map}}\nThe '''West Trenton Line''' is a proposed [[NJ Transit]] (NJT) commuter rail service that would be operated mostly on the [[CSX Transportation]] [[Trenton Subdivision (CSX Transportation)|Trenton Subdivision]], connecting [[West Trenton (SEPTA station)|West Trenton Station]] in [[Ewing Township, New Jersey]] with [[Pennsylvania Station (Newark)|Newark Penn Station]] in [[Newark, New Jersey]].<ref>http://www.njtpa.org/getattachment/Project-Programs/Project-Development/Study-and-Development-Program/081715_Detail-Report_2016-SD1.pdf.aspx</ref> The route would connect with the [[Raritan Valley Line]] at [[Bridgewater (NJT station)|Bridgewater]] and the [[SEPTA]] [[West Trenton Line (SEPTA)|West Trenton Line]] at West Trenton. {{As of|2007}}, NJT's estimate of the cost of creating a passenger line to West Trenton was $219 million.<ref name=\"njt\">{{cite web |url=http://www.njtransit.com/tm/tm_servlet.srv?hdnPageAction=Project016To |title=West Trenton Line |work=NJ Transit |accessdate=November 12, 2011}}</ref> The project is still on the books, but no funding for the proposal has been secured to this date.<ref name=\"njt\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/traffic/index.ssf/2015/05/will_commuter_trains_ever_roll_on_the_west_trenton_line_ask_commutinglarry_finds_out.html|title=Will commuter trains ever roll on the West Trenton Line? Ask @CommutingLarry finds out|website=NJ.com|access-date=May 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Former service==\n[[File:Belle Mead Station on the West Trenton.jpg|thumb|left|The Reading Company's Belle Mead station, which saw service until 1982]]\nHistorically, this was a property of the [[Reading Company]]. This line carried the Reading's ''[[Crusader (train)|Crusader]]'' and ''Wall Street'' trains, which originally operated as through service from [[Reading Terminal]] in [[Philadelphia]] to [[Communipaw Terminal]] in [[Jersey City]] (after 1965, to Newark). Until 1958, [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] long distance trains such as the ''[[Royal Blue (train)|Royal Blue]]'' to [[Washington, D.C.]], ''[[Capitol Limited (B&O train)]]'' to Chicago and the ''[[National Limited]]'' to St. Louis traveled on this line as well. \n\nThe Philadelphia-Newark service, like many former Reading and CNJ lines, was eventually subsidized by [[SEPTA]] and [[New Jersey Transit]]. In the early 1980s, SEPTA began cutting back [[SEPTA diesel service|its diesel-powered lines]] in preparation for the opening of the electric-only [[Center City Commuter Connection]]. Through service from Philadelphia to Newark ended on July 30, 1981; SEPTA continued service on its electric [[West Trenton Line (SEPTA)|West Trenton Line]], with a connection to a once-daily, weekday-only West Trenton-Newark shuttle using [[Budd Rail Diesel Car]]s.<ref name=dvarp>{{cite journal |url=http://dvarp.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009/07/dvrp9303.txt |title=New Backing for \"Crusader\" Route |first=John |last=Pawson |journal=The Delaware Valley Rail Passenger |date=March 1993 |volume=13 |issue=3 |publisher=Delaware Valley Association of Railroad Passengers}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Reading Company In Color |volume=1 |first=Jeremy F. |last=Plant |publisher=Morning Sun Books |year=1998 |isbn=9781878887955}}</ref> This service ended on December 3, 1982, when the NJ Transit shuttle made its final trip due to poor ridership and a budget deficit.<ref name=dec3>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/220014709/ |title=Rail service terminations opposed |first=Tom |last=Kehoe |newspaper=Courier News |page=12 |date=December 2, 1982 |via=Newspapers.com |url-access=subscription }}</ref> The trip served 290 daily passengers and cost $319,000 annually to run.<ref name=dvarp /> The three stops discontinued were Belle Mead, Hopewell and West Trenton.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rrpicturearchives.net/pictures/13487/1980map.jpg|title=Passenger Rail System State of New Jersey|last=|first=|date=1980|website=rrpicturearchives.net|publisher=New Jersey Transit|access-date=May 8, 2016}}</ref> New Jersey Transit still retained operating rights over the line.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/11/12/nyregion/the-region-rail-service-to-end-on-a-trenton-line.html|title=THE REGION; Rail Service to End On a Trenton Line|last=Times|first=Special To The New York|date=November 12, 1982|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=May 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Proposal==\n[[File:Hopewell, New Jersey, passenger rail station, June 2013 2.JPG|thumb|right|Hopewell station, served until 1981, would be served again under the proposal]]\nPresently, the route is owned by CSX Transportation; all station platforms have been removed except at West Trenton, which is currently used by the [[West Trenton Line (SEPTA)|West Trenton Line]], a SEPTA commuter service to Philadelphia which also operates on the Trenton Subdivision.\n\nAdditional track would be added to the existing right-of-way as part of the plan. A second track would be installed between the Sunnymeade Road grade crossing and [[Port Reading Junction]], where the West Trenton Line diverges from the Lehigh Line, for a distance of 2.8 miles. A second track would also be installed between Pennington \u2013 Hopewell Road Bridge and the Belle Mead station for a distance of 10 miles. Track would also be restored on the Reading Connector, an abandoned railroad right-of-way that ran between Port Reading Junction and the Raritan Valley Line. According to a 2007 plan, there would be 14 daily trains, five peak trains in each direction, one morning outbound train to West Trenton, one evening inbound train to Newark, and one midday train in each direction. Travel time would be 80 minutes from West Trenton to Newark. There would be an estimated 2,660 daily trips on the restored line. 13.1 acres of land would be acquired for a West Trenton rail yard.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.njtransit.com/pdf/AppK_Public_Involvement.pdf|title=Proposed Restoration of Passenger Rail Service on the West Trenton Line Appendix K: Public Involvement|last=|first=|date=November 2007|website=njtransit.com|publisher=New Jersey Transit|access-date=May 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nCommunities along the rail line, such as Hopewell Township have supported the planned restoration of the line.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.centraljersey.com/news/hopewell_valley_news/hopewell-township-supports-rail-line-revival/article_bf6a4e66-5720-5f2b-867e-3396407d7006.html|title=Hopewell Township supports rail line revival|last=Writer|first=John Tredrea, Staff|website=CentralJersey.com|access-date=May 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Proposed new stations==\n*'''[[West Trenton station|West Trenton]]''' (Connection with [[West Trenton Line (SEPTA)|SEPTA West Trenton Line]] service)\n*[[Interstate 295 (New Jersey)|I-295]] / Hopewell (Township)\n*[[Hopewell station|Hopewell (Borough)]]\n*[[Belle Mead station|Belle Mead]]\n*Hillsborough\n\nTrains would continue along the Raritan Valley Line from [[Bridgewater (NJT station)|Bridgewater]] to Newark Penn Station.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.njtransit.com/pdf/001_AlignmentMap_1207.pdf Map of the proposed service]\n\n{{New Jersey Transit Rail}}\n\n[[Category:NJ Transit Rail Operations]]\n[[Category:Proposed railway lines in New Jersey]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the proposed New Jersey Transit line|the SEPTA Regional Rail line|West Trenton Line (SEPTA)}}\n{{West Trenton Line Map}}\nThe '''West Trenton Line''' is a proposed [[NJ Transit]] (NJT) commuter rail service that would be operated mostly on the [[CSX Transportation]] [[Trenton Subdivision (CSX Transportation)|Trenton Subdivision]], connecting [[West Trenton (SEPTA station)|West Trenton Station]] in [[Ewing Township, New Jersey]] with [[Pennsylvania Station (Newark)|Newark Penn Station]] in [[Newark, New Jersey]].<ref>http://www.njtpa.org/getattachment/Project-Programs/Project-Development/Study-and-Development-Program/081715_Detail-Report_2016-SD1.pdf.aspx</ref> The route would connect with the [[Raritan Valley Line]] at [[Bridgewater (NJT station)|Bridgewater]] and the [[SEPTA]] [[West Trenton Line (SEPTA)|West Trenton Line]] at West Trenton. {{As of|2007}}, NJT's estimate of the cost of creating a passenger line to West Trenton was $219 million.<ref name=\"njt\">{{cite web |url=http://www.njtransit.com/tm/tm_servlet.srv?hdnPageAction=Project016To |title=West Trenton Line |work=NJ Transit |accessdate=2011-11-12}}</ref> The project is still on the books, but no funding for the proposal has been secured to this date.<ref name=\"njt\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/traffic/index.ssf/2015/05/will_commuter_trains_ever_roll_on_the_west_trenton_line_ask_commutinglarry_finds_out.html|title=Will commuter trains ever roll on the West Trenton Line? Ask @CommutingLarry finds out|website=NJ.com|access-date=2016-05-08}}</ref>\n\n==Former service==\n[[File:Belle Mead Station on the West Trenton.jpg|thumb|left|The Reading Company's Belle Mead station, which saw service until 1982]]\nHistorically, this was a property of the [[Reading Company]]. This line carried the Reading's ''[[Crusader (train)|Crusader]]'' and ''Wall Street'' trains, which originally operated as through service from [[Reading Terminal]] in [[Philadelphia]] to [[Communipaw Terminal]] in [[Jersey City]] (after 1965, to Newark). Until 1958, [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] long distance trains such as the ''[[Royal Blue (train)|Royal Blue]]'' to [[Washington, D.C.]], ''[[Capitol Limited (B&O train)]]'' to Chicago and the ''[[National Limited]]'' to St. Louis traveled on this line as well. \n\nThe Philadelphia-Newark service, like many former Reading and CNJ lines, was eventually subsidized by [[SEPTA]] and [[New Jersey Transit]]. In the early 1980s, SEPTA began cutting back [[SEPTA diesel service|its diesel-powered lines]] in preparation for the opening of the electric-only [[Center City Commuter Connection]]. Through service from Philadelphia to Newark ended on July 30, 1981; SEPTA continued service on its electric [[West Trenton Line (SEPTA)|West Trenton Line]], with a connection to a once-daily, weekday-only West Trenton-Newark shuttle using [[Budd Rail Diesel Car]]s.<ref name=dvarp>{{cite journal |url=http://dvarp.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009/07/dvrp9303.txt |title=New Backing for \"Crusader\" Route |first=John |last=Pawson |journal=The Delaware Valley Rail Passenger |date=March 1993 |volume=13 |issue=3 |publisher=Delaware Valley Association of Railroad Passengers}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Reading Company In Color |volume=1 |first=Jeremy F. |last=Plant |publisher=Morning Sun Books |year=1998 |isbn=9781878887955}}</ref> This service ended on December 3, 1982, when the NJ Transit shuttle made its final trip due to poor ridership and a budget deficit.<ref name=dec3>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/220014709/ |title=Rail service terminations opposed |first=Tom |last=Kehoe |newspaper=Courier News |page=12 |date=December 2, 1982 |via=Newspapers.com |url-access=subscription }}</ref> The trip served 290 daily passengers and cost $319,000 annually to run.<ref name=dvarp /> The three stops discontinued were Belle Mead, Hopewell and West Trenton.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rrpicturearchives.net/pictures/13487/1980map.jpg|title=Passenger Rail System State of New Jersey|last=|first=|date=1980|website=rrpicturearchives.net|publisher=New Jersey Transit|access-date=May 8, 2016}}</ref> New Jersey Transit still retained operating rights over the line.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/11/12/nyregion/the-region-rail-service-to-end-on-a-trenton-line.html|title=THE REGION; Rail Service to End On a Trenton Line|last=Times|first=Special To The New York|date=1982-11-12|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-05-08}}</ref>\n\n==Proposal==\n[[File:Hopewell, New Jersey, passenger rail station, June 2013 2.JPG|thumb|right|Hopewell station, served until 1981, would be served again under the proposal]]\nPresently, the route is owned by CSX Transportation; all station platforms have been removed except at West Trenton, which is currently used by the [[West Trenton Line (SEPTA)|West Trenton Line]], a SEPTA commuter service to Philadelphia which also operates on the Trenton Subdivision.\n\nAdditional track would be added to the existing right-of-way as part of the plan. A second track would be installed between the Sunnymeade Road grade crossing and [[Port Reading Junction]], where the West Trenton Line diverges from the Lehigh Line, for a distance of 2.8 miles. A second track would also be installed between Pennington \u2013 Hopewell Road Bridge and the Belle Mead station for a distance of 10 miles. Track would also be restored on the Reading Connector, an abandoned railroad right-of-way that ran between Port Reading Junction and the Raritan Valley Line. According to a 2007 plan, there would be 14 daily trains, five peak trains in each direction, one morning outbound train to West Trenton, one evening inbound train to Newark, and one midday train in each direction. Travel time would be 80 minutes from West Trenton to Newark. There would be an estimated 2,660 daily trips on the restored line. 13.1 acres of land would be acquired for a West Trenton rail yard.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.njtransit.com/pdf/AppK_Public_Involvement.pdf|title=Proposed Restoration of Passenger Rail Service on the West Trenton Line Appendix K: Public Involvement|last=|first=|date=November 2007|website=njtransit.com|publisher=New Jersey Transit|access-date=May 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nCommunities along the rail line, such as Hopewell Township have supported the planned restoration of the line.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.centraljersey.com/news/hopewell_valley_news/hopewell-township-supports-rail-line-revival/article_bf6a4e66-5720-5f2b-867e-3396407d7006.html|title=Hopewell Township supports rail line revival|last=Writer|first=John Tredrea, Staff|website=CentralJersey.com|access-date=2016-05-08}}</ref>\n\n==Proposed new stations==\n*'''[[West Trenton station|West Trenton]]''' (Connection with [[West Trenton Line (SEPTA)|SEPTA West Trenton Line]] service)\n*[[Interstate 295 (New Jersey)|I-295]] / Hopewell (Township)\n*[[Hopewell station|Hopewell (Borough)]]\n*[[Belle Mead station|Belle Mead]]\n*Hillsborough\n\nTrains would continue along the Raritan Valley Line from [[Bridgewater (NJT station)|Bridgewater]] to Newark Penn Station.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.njtransit.com/pdf/001_AlignmentMap_1207.pdf Map of the proposed service]\n\n{{New Jersey Transit Rail}}\n\n[[Category:NJ Transit Rail Operations]]\n[[Category:Proposed railway lines in New Jersey]]\n", "name_user": "Kew Gardens 613", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/West_Trenton_Line_(NJ_Transit)"}
{"title_page": "Golla (caste)", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Rajakambalam|the article |Rajakambalam}}\n\n{{Short description|Caste from South India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n\n{{infobox caste\n| caste_name             = Golla\n| classification         =\n| country                = {{unbulleted list\n | [[India]]\n }}\n| region                 = {{unbulleted list\n | [[Andhra Pradesh]]\n | [[Telangana]]\n | [[Tamil Nadu]]\n | [[Karnataka]]\n }}\n| languages              ={{unbulleted list\n | [[Telugu language|Telugu]] , [[Kannada]], [[Tulu language|Tulu]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n }}\n| religions              = [[Image:AUM symbol, the primary (highest) name of the God as per the Vedas.svg|15px]] [[Hinduism]] \n| ethnicity               =\n[[Aryans]] }}\n\n'''Golla''':-  Golla Naidu (or) Nayakkars are known as Telugu-speaking [[Yadava]]s in the [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Telangana]], [[Tamil Nadu|Tamilnadu]], [[Karnataka]] castes list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Writereaddata/cl/karnataka.pdf|title=CENTRAL LIST OF OBCs FOR THE STATE OF KARNATAKA|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bcmbcmw.tn.gov.in/obc/faq/andhrapradesh.pdf|title=CENTRAL LIST OF OBCs FOR THE STATE OF ANDHRA PRADESH|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  According to the document, there were 15,38,031 people in India based on the population census taken in 1911.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dspace.gipe.ac.in/xmlui/bitstream/handle/10973/18956/GIPE-016854.pdf?sequence=3&isAllowed=y|title=India Caste Census 1911|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> According to the current census of Andhra Pradesh Gollas contributes 7% of the population in the state and also Gollas are the dominant community in the districts of [[West Godavari]] and [[Cuddapah]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/rice-bowl-voters-may-tilt-the-scales/article27580287.ece|title='Rice bowl' voters may tilt the scales|last=W.chandrakanth|date=2004-03-23|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-01-02|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/71028/13/13_chapter%25207.pdf|title=Political Ecology|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nGollas are a group of the Nayakkar traditions who were migrated from Andhra Pradesh to Tamil Nadu, Karnataka, etc. They are commonly known as [[Naidu]] or Naicker.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite journal|date=September 1910|title=The Castes and Tribes of Southern India 1|journal=Nature|volume=84|issue=2134|pages=365\u2013367|doi=10.1038/084365a0|issn=0028-0836|bibcode=1910Natur..84..365.|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/8e35f3ed6744e9eecce4420277908f2f40e217ef}}</ref> They are also called \"[[Vatuka|Vadukar]]\" <ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.172487|title=The Madura Country A Manual I To V|last=G.h.nelson|date=1989}}</ref> in Tamil because, they came from the north of Tamil Nadu and also known as [[Rajakambalam Nayakar|Rajakambalatar]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.m.wikisource.org/wiki/Castes_and_Tribes_of_Southern_India/Tottiyan|title=Castes and Tribes of Southern India/Tottiyan - Wikisource, the free online library|website=en.m.wikisource.org|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> in Tamil Nadu. The word Kambalattar is derived from two major reasons they are:- \n* \"Kambalathar\" is from the word of [[Kampili kingdom|Kampili]] (Bellary). Gollas who came from [[Kampili kingdom|Kampili region]] (Bellary) are known as Kambalathar.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Singh|first=Kumar Suresh|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=YBEwAQAAIAAJ&q=kambalattar&dq=kambalattar&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjCsqv56sPnAhXFpOkKHcQyBCAQ6AEIUjAG|title=People of India|last2=India|first2=Anthropological Survey of|date=2001|publisher=Anthropological Survey of India|isbn=978-81-85938-88-2|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Singh|first=Kumar Suresh|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=1lZuAAAAMAAJ&dq=India's+Communities+madurai+nayaka&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=+madurai+nayaka|title=India's Communities|date=1998|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-563354-2|language=en}}</ref>\n* The Word \"Kambal\" meaning ''blanket'' and referred to three endogamous divisions namely, Vekkili, Thokala and Yerrakolla.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Ramesh|first=K. V.|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Svasti_%C5%9Ar%C4%AB.html?id=bAaFAAAAIAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Svasti \u015ar\u012b: Dr. B.Ch. Chhabra felicitation volume|last2=Prasad|first2=Agam|last3=Tewari|first3=S. P.|date=1984|publisher=Agam|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Ethnicity of the Golla Community==\n\n===Gollas were Aryans===\n* In the Book \" Bharata Desada Kurubar Charitre\" by [[V. R. Hanumanthaiah]] stated that {{cquote| The Shepherds belonged to the [[Aryan]] race. While making his thesis statement, he had referred to the various references to the shepherds in the Vedic literature. According to his study, the primary occupations of the Aryans were [[animal husbandry]] and weaving blankets, besides [[agriculture]]. He goes on to state that the shepherds were variously called as Avipal, Ajapal, Meshapal, Gopal during the [[Vedic period]] and that these people are at present known across the country with a variety of names |||V.R.Hanumanthaiah <ref>{{citation |first=V. R|last=Hanumanthaiah  |title=Bharata Deshada Kurbar Charitre  |year=1942|publisher=Karnatak Kurbar Sangha Publication|page=46}}</ref>}}\n* In The Book \" Karnataka Veera Kshatriyaru \" by [[S. B. Joshi]] states that the shepherds were descendants of the [[Aryans]]. He further states that{{cquote| The Term Kambali (blanket) has been recognised in the Vedic literature. Besides, he states that there are slokas in the [[Rig Veda]] that were recited by the Gollas while praying \u2018Pushan\u2019 (Sun) venerating him as the protector of their sheep. The following is the verse quoted in this context:-'''Where the grass is green and abundant,Where the grass appears beautiful In that blissful site let our sheep Thrive, and afford us good pasture,And such lands, and give us the strength in battles.20'''.  The above references provide evidences that there was a community of [[shepherds]] among the Aryans. The scholars referred above have, therefore, declared that the present day shepherds be treated as the descendants of the Aryan race. The argument that the shepherds belonged to the [[Aryan]] race was not a recent phenomenon, but is based on the premise that there existed communities that reared animals even during the Vedic period|||S.B.Joshi <ref>{{citation |first=Joshi|last=S.B  |title=Karnataka Veera Kshatriyaru (in Kannada)|publisher=Mysore Government Press|page=17}}</ref>}}\n\n==Origin of the caste ==\n[[File:Krishna in Brindavana.jpg|thumb|200px|Lord Sri Krishna]]\n* ''The'' ''Golla'' and their tribes claims to be the descendants of [[Yayati]] king of the [[Mahabharata]]. Yayati king had six sons. The last of them was a son of Kariyawala. His name is Avulu Amrithamaya. He had sons named Oli Raju and Simhadri Raju. The descendants of this tradition are Bedha Raju, Erunuka Raju, Nalunuka Raju and Polla Raju. The Golla people claim themselves as the descendants of these kings in the Mahabharata. Further, they are the Ahir (pastoral) descendants of [[Krishna|Sri Krishna]]. The Ahirs were belonged, and thus were members of the  \"''[[Kshatriya]]''\" (warrior) class in the Hindu ''[[Varna]]'' system.<ref name=\"Pandey2005\">{{cite book|author=Aditya Pandey|title=South Asia: Politics of South Asia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LaINywMCwgAC&pg=PA181|year=2005|publisher=Gyan Publishing House|isbn=978-81-8205-303-8|pages=181\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.m.wikisource.org/wiki/Castes_and_Tribes_of_Southern_India/Golla|title=Castes and Tribes of Southern India/Golla - Wikisource, the free online library|website=en.m.wikisource.org|access-date=2019-12-24}}</ref>\n* In the third volume of their book \u201cCastes and Tribes of Central Provinces\u201d, R.V. Russel and Hiralal give a different version as to the origins of Gollas. They state that [[Shiva|Lord Mahadeva]] had created the Gollas to take care of his sheep. Hence the shepherds among the Gollas consider him as the progenitor of their clan.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.211521|title=The Tribes And Castes Of The Central Provinces Of India Vol-iii|last=Russell R. V.|date=1916}}</ref>\n* Nanjundayya & Ananthakrishna Iyer states that the Gollas are the descendants of the progeny of a [[Brahmin]] woman and a [[Kshatriya]] man. They lived in Brindavan, rearing animals and eking their livelihood by selling dairy products. Since Lord Sri Krishna spent his childhood among the Gollas, it is said that the [[Yadava]] clan of Sri Krishna is of the same community. It is also stated that they lived in Repalle village at the beginning of [[Kali Yuga|Kali Yug]]. During the reign of Rajaraja Narendra, it was said that they immigrated to southern regions from Repalle. It is because of the above inferences, the Gollas consider themselves to belong to the Yadava clan or Golla kings. The very term Golla kings asserts their kinship with [[Krishna|Sri Krishna]], besides asserting them to be of a higher stratum of the society. Nanjundayya and Ananthakrishna Iyer refer to the last inference in the third volume of their book \u201cThe Mysore Tribes & Castes\u201d.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.22885|title=The Mysore Tribes And Castes Vol. 3|last=Iyer|first=L. K. Ananthakrishna|date=1930}}</ref>\n\n==Sub-Castes of Golla==\n{{OSM Location map\n| coord = {{coord|15.0950|N|76.5488|E}}   <!-- Map center -->\n| float = right\n| zoom = 8\n| width = 300 <!-- width and height of the frame. numeric input - do not add px -->\n| height = 270\n| caption = <center>Kampili Nadu Region</center>\n| minimap = \n| mini-file = \n| mini-width = \n| mini-height = \n| minipog-x = \n| minipog-y = \n| scalemark = \n| shape = \n<!--Tumati -->\n| mark-coord1 = {{coord|15.1021|N|76.7762|E}}\n| mark1 = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size1 = 8\n| label1 = Tumati\n| label-size1 = 10\n| label-color1 = red\n| label-pos1 = left\n| mark-title1 = [[Tumati]]\n| mark-image1 =\n| mark-description1 = Tumati\n<!--Hoovina Hadagali -->\n| mark-coord2 = {{coord|15.0200|N|75.9318|E}}\n| mark2 = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size2 = 8\n| label2 = Hadagali\n| label-size2 = 14\n| label-color2 = black\n| label-pos2 = bottom\n| mark-title2 = [[Hoovina Hadagali]]\n| mark-image2 =\n| mark-description2 = Hadagali\n<!-- Ballari -->\n| mark-coord3 = {{coord| 15.1394|N|76.9214|E}}\n| mark3 = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size3 = 10\n| label3 = Ballari\n| label-size3 = 14\n| label-color3 = black\n| label-pos3 = bottom\n| mark-title3 = [[Ballari]]\n| mark-image3 =\n| mark-description3 = Ballari\n<!-- Kampli -->\n| mark-coord4 = {{coord|15.4063 |N|76.6052|E}} \n| mark4 = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size4 = 8\n| label4 = Kampli\n| label-size4 = 20\n| label-color4 = black\n| label-pos4 = top\n| mark-title4 = [[Kampli]]\n| mark-image4 =\n| mark-description4 = Kampli\n<!-- Hampi -->\n| mark-coord5 = {{coord|15.3350|N|76.4600|E}} \n| mark5 = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size5 = 8\n| label5 = Hampi\n| label-size5 = 10\n| label-color5 = red\n| label-pos5 = bottom\n| mark-title5 = [[Hampi]]\n| mark-image5 =\n| mark-description5 = Hampi\n<!-- Kotturu -->\n| mark-coord6 = {{coord|14.8267|N|76.2218|E}}\n| mark6 = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size6 = 8\n| label6 = Kotturu\n| label-size6 = 10\n| label-color6 = red\n| label-pos6 = right\n| mark-title6 = [[Kotturu, Karnataka|Kotturu]]\n| mark-image6 =\n| mark-description6 = Kotturu\n<!-- Sandur -->\n| mark-coord7 = {{coord|15.0874|N|76.5477|E}}\n| mark7 = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size7 = 8\n| label7 = Sandur\n| label-size7 = 10\n| label-color7 = red\n| label-pos7 = left\n| mark-title7 = [[Sandur, India|Sandur]]\n| mark-image7 =\n| mark-description7 = Sandur\n<!-- Siruguppa -->\n| mark-coord8 = {{coord|15.6175|N|76.9006|E}}\n| mark8 = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size8 = 10\n| label8 = Siruguppa\n| label-size8 = 14\n| label-color8 = black\n| label-pos8 = top\n| mark-title8 = [[Siruguppa]]\n| mark-image8 =\n| mark-description8 = Sirupuppa\n<!-- Davnagiri -->\n| mark-coord9 = {{coord|14.4644|N|75.9218|E}}\n| mark9 = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size9 = 10\n| label9 = Davnagiri\n| label-size9 = 14\n| label-color9 = black\n| label-pos9 = top\n| mark-title9 = [[Davnagiri]]\n| mark-image9 =\n| mark-description9 = Davnagiri\n<!-- Tungabhadra River -->\n| mark-coord10 = {{coord|15.2615|N|76.3379|E}}<!-- {{coord|15.53|19|31|N| 78|09|51|45|E}} -->\n| mark10 = AS-rzeka-icon.svg\n| mark-size10 = 10\n| label10 = Tungabhadra River\n| label-size10 = 10\n| label-color10 = blue\n| label-pos10 = left\n| mark-title10 = [[Tungabhadra River]]\n| mark-image10 =\n| mark-description10 = Tungabhadra River\n<!-- Vedavathi river -->\n| mark-coord11 = {{coord|15.3541|N|76.5658|E}}\n| mark11 = AS-rzeka-icon.svg\n| mark-size11 = 10\n| label11 = Vedavathi River\n| label-size11 = 10\n| label-color11 = blue\n| label-pos11 = right\n| mark-title11 = [[Vedavati River]]\n| mark-image11 =\n| mark-description11 = Vedavathi River\n\n}}\n\n'''\"Golla\"''' the word came from Gopala. They are also called Konarulu in Tamil.There are many Sub-castes Classified under Golla They are:-\n\n* Astra Golla\n* Mond Golla\n* Kadu Golla (Kannada Speakers)\n* Uru Golla\n* Tumati<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wikimapia.org/15048006/Tumati-Village|title=Tumati Village|website=wikimapia.org|language=en|access-date=2019-12-24}}</ref> Golla<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n* Kona Golla<ref name=\":8\" />\n* Pooja Golla\n* Karna Golla\n* Patra Golla\n* Paknati Golla\n* Erra Golla\n* Tottiyan<ref>{{Cite journal|date=September 1910|title=The Castes and Tribes of Southern India 1 |journal=Nature|volume=84|issue=2134|pages=365\u2013367|doi=10.1038/084365a0|issn=0028-0836|bibcode=1910Natur..84..365. |url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/8e35f3ed6744e9eecce4420277908f2f40e217ef }}</ref>\n* Palavar<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|title=The political history of the Madura country, ancient and modern|last=Nelson |first=James Henry|date=1989|publisher=Asian Educational Services|oclc=49223435}}</ref>\n* Mekalavar<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=tQYlAAAAMAAJ&q=mekala+golla&dq=mekala+golla|title=Veeraghattam, a Declassified Town of Andhra Pradesh|last=Ramaswamy|first=E.|date=1975|publisher=Controller, Department of Publications|language=en}}</ref>\n* Thokala Golla<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=History of the N\u0101yaks of Madura|last=Sathianathaier, R.|date=1991|publisher=Asian Educational Services|isbn=81-206-0532-2|oclc=26876727}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=RwEJAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA45&dq=thokala+golla#v=onepage&q=thokala%20golla&f=false|title=Various Census of India|date=1883|language=en}}</ref>\n* Kuruma (Kuruba) Golla<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bheenaveni|first=Ram|title=Golla+Kuruma=Yadav (Gollakurumalu Okkate)|url=https://www.academia.edu/4541427|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n* Chillavar\n\nThese are some of the sub-castes of Golla.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://sg.inflibnet.ac.in/jspui/bitstream/10603/249829/6/06%20chapter-iii.pdf|title=Golla sub-castes|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.m.wikisource.org/wiki/Castes_and_Tribes_of_Southern_India/Kollar|title=Castes and Tribes of Southern India/Kollar - Wikisource, the free online library|website=en.m.wikisource.org|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> It is said to be that Kadu Golla originated from the banks of the river [[Ganges]] and the Uru Golla are native to [[Andhra Pradesh]]. They have no marriage bond among them. Astrandra means the court, which means that the sect was originally a people of justice for the Golla people. Tumati Golla are natives of ancient [[Bellary]] ([[Kampili kingdom|Kampili country]]). Although the Gollas are the social work of shepherding the orders, they have been great warriors and also as kings and poligars.\n\n== Medieval history==\n\n[[File:Daulatabad Fort a view.JPG|thumb|right|Devagiri Fort]]\nThe Gollas are believed to be originally the people from the kingdom of [[Yadava|Yadhavas]] who ruled parts of [[Andhra Pradesh|Andhra]] with their capital at Devagiri in the twelfth or thirteenth century.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://lsi.gov.in:8081/jspui/bitstream/123456789/6510/1/49346_1961_PAP.pdf&ved=2ahUKEwiK9OP68rznAhWCguYKHZI-CsEQFjAOegQICRAB&usg=AOvVaw1D-obnf8u5aJw_DcZMgUvf|title=Census of India 1961 Madras Volume 9|last=Nambiar|first=P.K.|date=1965|website=|publisher=Deputy Superintendent of Census Operations, Madras|page=8|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The Seuna kingdom reached its peak under [[Simhana|Simhana II]], and flourished until, when it was annexed by the [[Delhi Sultanate]]. After Gollas lost their throne of Devagiri.     The Gollas were appointed as feudatories and generals of the [[Kakatiya dynasty|Kakatiyas]]. When the Kakatiya dynasty was defeated by sultans The Golla Kakatiya generals Harihara and Bukka were subdued in jail. After this incident the Sultan appointed [[Harihara I|Harihara]] and [[Bukka Raya I|Bukka Raya]] as governors of the [[Kampili kingdom|Kampili country]] to prevent the Gollas from revolting. Robert Sewell recorded this in the Madras provincial government gazette.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n(Proof): Vijayanagar: As Seen by Domingos Paes and Fernao Nuniz (16th century Portuguese chroniclers and others)\n\n===Documentary on Golla (Yadava) kingdom===\n* ''Click the link below to see The Documentary (Telugu)''\n{{Website|https://vimeo.com/281747778|Golla Kingdom}}\n\n==Establishment of Vijayanagar Empire==\n\n[[File:vijayanagara flag.png|thumb|right|Vijayanagar Empire Flag]]\n\n[[Sringeri Sharada Peetham|Sringeri]] Monastery saint Vidyaranya converted Harihara and Bukha back to Vaishnavism. He assisted Harihara and Bukha in mobilizing the people of the area using revolutionary speeches. As the result, [[Vijayanagara Empire|Vijayanagar]] kingdom founded in 1336.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Vijayanagar: As Seen by Domingos Paes and Fernao Nuniz (16th Century Portuguese Chroniclers and Others)|last=Robert Sewell|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n[[Kumara Kampana|Kumara Kambana]] was the king of the Vijayanagara Empire. CE. In 1336, the Harihara and Bukka the Yadava Golla brothers, formed the Vijayanagara Empire. Kumara Kampana is the son of Bukka. In 1362 AD, he defeated Raja Narayana Sambuvaraya the king of Thondai Mandalam who's capital is [[Tiruvannamalai|Thiruvannamalai]] and Kumara Kampana conquered the Thondai Mandalam. He then invaded the [[Madurai]] Sultanate and ended the rule of the Sultans there. By AD 1364, the rule of the Mohammedans had begun to crumble. The struggle continued until 1378. Kumara Kampana was tasked with protecting the temple Endowments and recruiting many leaders to take on the responsibilities of Pandya Nadu.\n\nHis wife [[Gangadevi]], who was present during the invasion of Madurai, records the siege and conquest of Madurai in her Sanskrit treatise [[Madura Vijayam|Madhura Vijayam]].<ref name=\"Jackson2005\">{{cite book|author=William Joseph Jackson|title=Vijayanagara Voices: Exploring South Indian History and Hindu Literature|year=2005|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-3950-3|page=[http://books.google.com/books?id=PxvDNBc4qwUC&pg=PA61 61]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.tamilvu.org/slet/lA100/lA100pd1.jsp?bookid=224&pno=392 |title = Tvu}}</ref>\n\n==Sri Krishnadevaraya's Clan==\n\n[[File:vijayanagara.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Sri Krishnadevaraya]]\n\n* The Below informations are Published by [[Archeological Survey of India]] in the book \"Annual Report of the Mysore Archeological Department\".\n\n===Nanjagud Taluk Inscription Translation===\nBe it well. In the .victorious and prospering Salivahana era, 1431 years having\nexpired, while the year Srimukha was current, on the 5th lunar day of the dark\nhalf of Phalguna : \u2014 Be it well. Victory to the Adorable (Padmanabha) who resembles the sky free\nfrom clouds.While the illustrious Krishnavarma-mahadhiraja seated on the stable throne, \u2018the prosperous king of kings, lord of kings, champion over those who wear moustaches in the great earth, kathdri-sahwa (dagger and kite), ruler over the southern sea,\nNarasimha-mahadhiraja\u2019s son ; a sun to the firmament that is the [[Yadava]] race of\nwhich he is a lineal descendant ; crest-jewel to righteousness, (delighter) of all the\nassemblage of bards, brother to the wives of others, support for purity, heroism and prowess; possessed of lotus-like feet on which bow the jewelled crowns of all the kings, kathari-trinitra (a Siva in the use of dagger) : was ruling the earth :\u2014 Under the orders of vira Krishnaraya, while he was pleased to go on a victorious\nexpedition to the south : \u2014the illustrious mahapradhana (chief minister) Saluva\nTimmarasa of Yajus-sakha, Khandava-gotra, and Apastambha-sutra made a gift to the best of the gods, Kirtinarayanadevaru of [[Talakadu|Talakad]] which is Rajarajapura, south Benares and Gajaranya-kshetra, of the village Kavahalli in Thayuru-sthala, with the right to enjoy the eight rights and powers in the village including all the rice-fields, dry lands, gardens, vegetable gardens (tudike), money income, treasure, deposits underground, water springs, rocks, imperishables, future accruals, existing rights and possibilities. The said village Kalialli with its income amounting to 130 varahas and two hanas is granted for the three services, in the afternoon, of the god Kirtinarayana\nand the gift is made in the Pampa-kshetra which is the same as [[Vijayanagara|Vijayanagari]], on the banks of the Tungabhadra, and in the presence of the God Virhpaksha-linga on the above occasion, as a holy gift (Krishnarpana) with pouring of water and gold; and the village is made over, together with the procession images of the gods and goddesses at Vijayanagari and their ornaments, into the treasury of the god Kirtina-rayana, in order that the gift might last as long as the moon and sun endure. The gift of the village was made at the request of Upavasi Achariya of Bharadvaja gotra, Yajussakhe, and Apastamba-sutra, for the merit of Krishnaraya and Saluva Timma.Between making a gift and maintaining one already made, maintenance is better than gift. By a gift one obtains heaven and by protecting a gift one goes to a region from which there is no fall. Maintaining a gift made by others is twice as meritorious as making a gift oneself. By confiscating another\u2019s gift, one\u2019s own gift becomes fruitless. \u201cThis bridge of dharma is common to all kings and should be protected by you from time to time.\u201d Thus does Ramachandra beseech again and again all future rulers. He who seizes land gifted by himsolf or by others is borm as a worm in ordure for 60,000 years. Whoever destroys this gift will incur the sin of killing tawny cows on the banks of the [[Ganges]].<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.501532|title=Annual Report Of The Mysore Archaeological Department, For The Year 1930|first=M.H.|last=Krishna|date=1934|language=english}}</ref>\n\n'''Note'''\n\nThis is a record registering the grant of a village called Kavahalli or Kalihalli (same as the present village Kahalli) for services in the Kirtinarayana temple at Talakad on the Kaveri river in T.-Narsipur Taluk, Mysore District. It belongs to the reign of the [[Vijayanagara Empire|Vijayanagar]] king Krishnaraya and is dated S' 1434 Srimukha sam.\nPhal. ba. 5. This date corresponds to March 15, A. D. 1514, if we take S' 1434\nexpired or S' 1435 current Srimukha as the year intended. There are some peculiar features in the historical portion of this record. The king Krishnaraya is here styled Krishnavarma-mahadhiraja (L.8) as is aged the\ncase in two other inscriptions of the same Taluk (E. C. III. Nanjangud 190 and 195 of 1512 and 1513 A. D.). He is given some titles of the Western Gangas and [[Hoysala Empire|Hoysalas]]. (Jitam bhagavata gata-ghana-gaganabhena L.3, : Yadava-kulambara-dyumani samyaktva-chudamani). Another point to notice in this record is the mention of the king\u2019s visit to the southern part of his empire on a conquering expedition. Saluva Timmarasa and his brother Saluva Govindaraja were ministers of Krishnaraja and Govindaraja was entrusted with the government of Terakanambi kingdom (see E. C. IV [[Gundlupet]] 3 of S 1435 and 1 of S 1444, etc.,) and\nhis grants are frequently met with in the [[Nanjangud]], Chamarajanagar and\nGundlupet Taluks. (E. C. Ill Nanjangud 196 of S\u2019 1435; T.-Narsipur 42 of S\u2019 1445 ; T.-Narsipur 73 of S\u2019 1441 : E. C. IV Gundlup6t 1, 3, 35 ; [[Chamarajanagar]] 99 of S 1445, 111 etc.) In some of these records their gotra is given as Kaundinya\nand not as Khandava. The temple of Kirtinarayana at Talakad- is a Hoysala structure and is believed to have been constructed by king Vishnuvardhana (see M. A. R. 1912, p.&nbsp;11). Not only are the revenues of the village stated to have been granted for services in the temple but also the utsava-images of the god and goddesses with ornaments either newly prepared or bolonging to some other temple are said to have been sent from Vijayanagar, the capital. Lastly the grant is stated to have been made at\nthe instance of a [[Brahman]] named Upavasi- Achariya. The usual imprecatory stanzas are found at the end of the grant.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n* In The Book \"Sculptural Art of Hampi\" Published by Directorate of Archaeology and Museum,Mysore says as Below:-\n{{cquote| The Tuluvas claimed their descent from the Yadava Lineage.The earliest known member of this family is Isvaranayaka.|||Directorate of Archaeology and Museum, Mysore  '''<ref>{{Cite book| title=Sculptural Art of Hampi | volume=|first=K.M| last=Suresh| year=1998| page=21 | publisher=  Directorate of Archaeology and Museum,Mysore| url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=r7xmluMu-FsC&dq=tuluva+yadava&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=yadava }}</ref>}}\n\n==Formation of the Balija==\n*During the time of The Vijayanagara king [[Krishnadevaraya]], formed the business division called [[Balija]] by mobilizing '''Gollas''', [[Gavara]]s and many others under the title of 'Balija':<ref>{{cite book |last1=N\u0101r\u0101ya\u1e47ar\u0101vu |first1=V\u0113lc\u0113ru |last2=Rao |first2=Velcheru Narayana |last3=Shulman |first3=David Dean |last4=Subrahmanyam |first4=Sanjay |title=Symbols of substance: court and state in N\u0101yaka Period Tamilnadu |date=1992 |publisher=Oxford University Press |hdl=2027/heb.02449 |oclc=758445206 }}{{page needed|date=January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Subrahmanyam1992\">{{cite book|author=Velcheru Narayana Rao|author2==David Dean Shulman |author3=Sanjay Subrahmanyam|title= Symbols of substance: court and state in N\u0101yaka Period Tamilnadu|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1992|isbn=0-19-563021-1|page=74|quote=''These left-[[Shudra|Sudra]] groups \u2014 often referred to by the cover-title 'Balija', but also including [[Boyar caste|Boyas]], left-hand Gollas, [[Gavara]]s, and others - were first mobilized by [[Krishnadevaraya]] in the Vijayanagara heyday...These Balija fighters are not afraid of kings: some stories speak of their killing kings who interfered with their affairs\"}}</ref>\n* The Government Official Record \" Madras District Gazetteers\" by Honourable F.J.Richards (Indian Civil Services) says as below :-\n {{cquote| Balijas are reported to be mere occupational terms which do not indicate true Sub-castes.The Golla Balijas are probably '''Gollas''' (q.v.)who called themselves Naidus; the Kamma Balijas are perhaps to be identified with the [[Kamma (caste)|Kammas]] (q.v. p.166), and Linga Balija or Sivachar Kavarai appears to be the popular term for Kanarese [[Lingayats]].|||F.J.Richards <ref>{{citation |last= Richards |first= F.J. |title=MADRAS DISTRICT GAZETTEERS|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.281734/page/n191/mode/2up|year=1918 |publisher=GOVERNMENT PRESS|page=179}}</ref>}}\n\n==Establishment of Madurai Nayak Dynasty==\n[[File:Tnayak-edited.JPG|thumb|150px|Thirumala Nayakkar Statue in [[Madurai Meenakshi Temple]]]]\n\n[[Madurai Nayak dynasty|Mahamandaleshwara Nagama nayak]] the successful Commander-in-chief of Sri Krishnadevaraya's court and also the leader of Gollas, wanted to establish a new empire for the Gollas due domination by other castes in the Later [[Vijayanagara Empire|Vijayanagar Empire]] as chiefs and ministers. So, Nagama Nayak waited for the moment to start his riot to claim a separate Kingdom for Gollas. In [[Madurai]] (Pandya Nadu) at the time [[Chola dynasty|Chola King Veerasekhara Chola]] invades the Madurai Kingdom and deposed the [[Pandya dynasty|Pandya King Chandrasekhara Pandyan]], who was under the protection of Sri [[Krishnadevaraya]]. Due to this, an enraged Sri Krishnadevaraya sends Nagama Nayak to aid Chandrasekhara Pandyan. Nagama Nayak suppresses Veerasekhara Chola and takes Madurai, but then he used a situation to found empire for Golla. So, he threw off his allegiance and declining to help Chandrasekhara Pandyan, usurped the throne.\n\nSo, [[Viswanatha Nayak]] volunteers to face his father on the battle ground. Nagama Nayak is defeated and the loyalty of Viswanatha Nayak is proved. Chivalry of both father and son is admired by Sri Krishnadevaraya, who makes Viswanatha Nayak the Governor of Madurai and other regions.\nDue to this cause the [[Madurai Nayak dynasty|Madurai Nayak Empire]] founder in 1529 AD. Then Viswanatha Nayak became the first king of the empire  then, he divided Madurai regions in to 72 palayams (Zamins) and nearly 52 of the palayams were left under the control of Golla Rajakambalam by nominating them as [[Polygar|Poligars]] of the palayams and also Viswanatha Nayak designed his kingdom's flag with a symbol of '''poli avu (Poli Rishaba)''' means holy cow of Gollas in it.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aiyar|first=R. Sathyanatha|last2=Aiyangar|first2=S. Krishnaswami|date=1926|title=History of the Nayaks of Madura|journal=Journal of the American Oriental Society|volume=46|pages=94|doi=10.2307/593785|issn=0003-0279|jstor=593785}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jeyamohan.in/15|title=\u0bae\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bc8 \u0ba8\u0bbe\u0baf\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0bb5\u0bb0\u0bb2\u0bbe\u0bb1\u0bc1 (\u0b85.\u0b95\u0bbf.\u0baa\u0bb0\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0bae\u0ba9\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0b8e\u0bae\u0bcd.\u0b8f)|website=www.jeyamohan.in|access-date=2019-12-24}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===Gollas (or) Tottiyans Migration to Tamilnadu===\n\n[[Telugu people|Telugus]] from the north migrated and settled down in the Tamil-speaking areas in the south. Historians are of the opinion that  Vishvanatha Nayaka established the Nayaka dynasty at [[Madurai]] during Krishnadevaraya's regime, as early as AD 1529.During that period a large number of the Telugu who were brought from the Telugu state belonged to different castes like, The [[Komati caste|Vaisya]], Kamma, [[Velama]], [[Balija]], Yadava (Golla) and [[Gavara]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Jw9uAAAAMAAJ&dq=india's+communities+golla&q=Yadava|title=India's communities|last=Singh|first=Kumar Suresh|last2=India|first2=Anthropological Survey of|date=1998|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-563354-2|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Gollavar's Devarattam==\n{{main|Deverattam}}\n\"[[Deverattam|Devarattam]]\" is a Tamil Word derived from the words \"Devar\" or Thevar (Tamil meaning: the god/ king/ or warriors) + \"Attam\" (Tamil meaning: the dance).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sastri and Kallidaikurichi Aiyah Nilakanta |title=A history of South India from prehistoric times to the fall of Vijayanagar |date=1976 |publisher=Oxford University Press. |pages=20\u201321}}</ref> Traditionally, it was performed by the kings and warriors after a successful battle particularly in pandyan dynasty,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rajan. K. and Soundara. V |title=). Rock-cut temple styles: early Pandyan art and the Ellora shrines |date=1998 |publisher=Somaiya Publications |isbn=9788170392187 |pages=50\u201352}}</ref>\ndevarattam is performed mostly by the Rajakambalathu Nayakkar a [[Telugu language|Telugu]] origin community those who believes they are migrants from [[Andhra Pradesh]] also The Descendants of Vijayanagar dynasty of The South India and settled in Tamil Nadu for many generations.\ndevarattam was mostly performed only by the Rajakambalam dancers of the same community during the temple festivals and other functions in [[Tamil Nadu]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.india9.com/i9show/Devarattam-26478.htm |title=Devarattam in Madurai India |publisher=India9.com |date=2005-06-07 |accessdate=2012-02-10}}</ref>\n\n==Golla Poligars (Zamins)==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Tamilnadu Golla Poligars '''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vget.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/poligar_systein_Tamil_Country.pdf&ved=2ahUKEwjs0qC8v-nmAhU5zDgGHWDjC7sQFjAAegQIBBAB&usg=AOvVaw1yeo1jZw56OYWTxBoHy4tc|title=The Poligar System in Tamil country:its Origin and Growth|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" />\n|+(Out of 72 Palems)\n!S.no\n!Name of the Palem\n!Name of the Poligar\n|-\n| 1.\n|Era Chakka Nayakanur\n|Kandhappa Nayakkar\n|-\n| 2.\n|[[Thevaram]]\n|     -\n|-\n| 3.\n|[[Bodinayakkanur|Bodinayakanur]]\n|Thirumalai Bodi Nayakar\n|-\n| 4.\n|[[Panchalankurichi]]\n|[[Veerapandiya Kattabomman|Veerapandiya Kattabommu Nayakkar]]\n|-\n| 5.\n|[[Ettayapuram]]\n|Jegaveera Pandya Ettappa Nayakar\n|-\n| 6.\n|Ammaya Nayakanur\n|Kathira Nayakkar\n|-\n| 7.\n|[[Ambathurai|Ambathturai]]\n|Makala Nayakkar\n|-\n| 8.\n|Davasu Madai\n|Sudalai Nayakkar\n|-\n| 9.\n|Emmakalapuram\n| -\n|-\n| 10.\n|Maranadu\n|Chinna Alagiri Nayakkar\n|-\n| 11.\n|Madhur\n|Venkatasamy Nayakar\n|-\n| 12.\n|[[Chokkampatti]]\n|Pallamuthu Nayakkar\n|-\n| 13.\n|[[Eriyodu]]\n|Muthu Kumaravelu Nayakkar\n|-\n| 14.\n|Palliappa Nayakanur\n|Palliyappa Nayakkar\n|-\n| 15.\n|Idayakottai\n|Mambara Nayakkar\n|-\n| 16.\n|Mambara\n|Sakaram Dhoma Nayakkar\n|-\n| 17.\n|[[Palani]]\n|Velayudha Nayakkar\n|-\n| 18.\n|[[Ayakudi]]\n|Kondama Nayakkar\n|-\n| 19.\n|[[Virupakshipuram|Virupakshi]]\n|Kuppala Nayakkar\n|-\n| 20.\n|[[Kannivadi, Dindigul|Kannivadi]]\n|Andiyappa Nayakkar\n|-\n| 21.\n|Nagalapuram\n|Soundara Pandya Nayakkar\n|-\n| 22.\n|Ethilappa Nayakan Patti\n|Thali Ethilappa Nayakkar\n|-\n| 23.\n|Kadalkudi\n| -\n|-\n| 24.\n|[[Kulathur,Pudukkottai|Kulathur]]\n| -\n|-\n| 25.\n|Melmandhai\n| -\n|-\n| 26.\n|Aatrangarai\n| -\n|-\n| 27.\n|Kolarpatti\n| -\n|-\n| 28.\n|[[Kadambur]]\n| -\n|-\n| 29.\n|Sinjuvadi\n| Sampae Nayakkar\n|-\n| 30.\n|Thottappa Nayakanur\n| -\n|-\n| 31.\n|[[Cumbum, Tamil Nadu|Cumbum]]\n| -\n|-\n| 32.\n|Kasiyur\n| -\n|-\n| 33.\n|Varappur\n| -\n|-\n| 34.\n|Athippatti\n| -\n|-\n| 35.\n|[[Kandama Nayakkanur]]\n|Swami Aandi Velappa Nayakkar\n|-\n| 36.\n|Tumbichi Nayakanur\n|Tumbichi Nayakkar\n|-\n| 37.\n|Innasipuram\n| -\n|-\n| 38.\n|Sakkanti\n| -\n|-\n| 39.\n|[[Periyakulam]]\n| -\n|-\n| 40.\n|[[Kuruvikulam]]\n| -\n|-\n| 41.\n|Ilasai\n| -\n|-\n| 42.\n|Madhuvarpatti\n| -\n|-\n| 43.\n|[[Theni]]\n| -\n|-\n| 44.\n|[[Vadakarai Keezhpadugai|Vadakarai]]\n| -\n|-\n| 45.\n|Malayapatti\n| -\n|-\n| 46.\n|Rosalai Patti\n| -\n|-\n| 47.\n|Padamattur\n| -\n|-\n| 48.\n|Ezhumalai\n| -\n|-\n| 49.\n|Avalappan patti\n| Avalappa Nayakkar\n|-\n| 50.\n|[[Nilakkottai|Nilakottai]]\n| -\n|-\n| 51.\n|Mulliyur\n| -\n|-\n| 52.\n|Koppaya Nayakanur\n|Koppaya Nayakkar\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Andra Pradesh Golla Poligars '''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/62877/8/08_chapter%25203.pdf&ved=2ahUKEwiD0KqrvenmAhV3zDgGHe-lAE8QFjABegQIARAB&usg=AOvVaw3i2WNEQIzrwvdiE-F_dBqw|title=The Origin and Development of Polegar System|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|+(Out of 72 Palems)\n!S.no\n!Name of the Palem\n!Name of the Poligar\n|-\n| 1.\n|[[Kothakota]]\n|Perumappa Nair\n|-\n| 2.\n|Kapadrala\n|Chota Maddappa Nair\n|-\n| 3.\n|Dudikonda\n|Mullappa Nair\n|-\n| 4.\n|Bandicona\n|Rama Nair\n|-\n| 5.\n|Pandikona\n|Venkatappa Naidu\n|-\n| 6.\n|Maddikera\n|Mallikarjuna Naidu\n|-\n| 7.\n|Aspari\n|Gurgiji Yellana Rayudu\n|-\n| 8.\n|Yagarlapalem\n|Purusarama Naidu\n|-\n| 9.\n|Mandapampalem\n|Bakke Yellam Naidu\n|-\n| 10.\n|Janulavaram\n|Basivi Naidu\n|-\n| 11.\n|Palakondapanayanipalli\n|Machineni Kondappa Naidu\n|-\n| 12.\n|Putturpalem\n|Duli bsi Naidu\n|-\n| 13.\n|Gonarajupalem\n|Yerrabasivi Naidu\n|-\n| 14.\n|[[Thondur]]\n|Pedda Gopala Naidu\n|-\n| 15.\n|Senumumballi\n|Pappa Naidu\n|-\n| 16.\n|Kondareddipalli\n|Timmala Naidu\n|-\n| 17.\n|[[Kothakota]]\n|Chinna Gopal Naidu\n|-\n| 18.\n|Dasari Palli\n|Veeraneyini Siddhapa Naidu\n|-\n| 19.\n|Yakarlapalem\n|Veeraneyini Vithalapathi Naidu\n|-\n| 20.\n|Mudireddipalem\n|Pedda Nagappa Naidu\n|}\n\n==Social status==\n[[File:Indian Caste System.jpg|thumb|Indian Hindu Varna System]]\n\n===Ramasvami Choudary's Theory===\n* According to Ramasvami chowdary the classification of different caste and their occupations in [[south india]] before the aryan occupation conformed to the following hierarchical order:\n{{cquote| 1. Golla, [[Vanniyar|Palli]], Kummari and other such castes:Priests analogous to Bramins of Aryan society. \n2. Land owning castes like Kammas, [[Reddy|Reddis]], Velamas:Warriers/Kings,analogous to Kshatriyas of Aryan society.\n\n3. Balija, [[Komati (caste)|Komati]], [[Swakula Sali|Sali]] and other such castes:Trading castes analogous to Viashyas of Aryan society.\n\n4. Kasa, Boya, Cakali and other similar service castes: Servants analogous to Shudras of Aryan society.|||Ramasvami Choudary '''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Questioning Ramayanas: A South Asian Tradition |first=Paula| last=Richman|year=2000 |isbn=9780520923751|page=176 |publisher=University of California Press|url=https://books.google.com/?id=7RW6MrAiJ-0C&q=Golla#v=snippet&q=Golla&f=false}}</ref>}}\n* The Golla are considered to be the [[Yadu]]-[[Chandravanshi]] [[Kshatriya]] class as per the traditional Hindu ritual ranking known as [[Varna (Hinduism)|Varna system]].<ref name=\"Pandey2005\" />\n* In the book [[Castes and Tribes of Southern India|Caste And Tribes of Southern India Volume-2]] by [[Edgar Thurston]], he explained the quote of Mr.Stuart that is given below indicates the social status of Gollas.{{cquote|Mr. Stuart writes further that the social status of the Gollas is fairly high, for they are allowed to mix freely with the [[Kapu (caste)|Kapu]], [[Kamma (caste)|Kamma]], and [[Balija]] castes, and the [[Brahmin|Brahmans]] will take buttermilk from their hands. They employ Satanis as their priests. In their ceremonies there is not much difference between them and the Kapus.|||H.A.Stuart '''<ref>{{Cite book| title=The Castes and Tribes of Southern India | volume=|first=Edgar| last=Thurston| authorlink= Edgar thurston|year=1909| page=311 | publisher=Madras Government press| isbn=0-299-06740-8| url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.47735/page/n311}}</ref>}}\n\n===Government classifications===\n* Most of The Gollas are classified and listed as a [[Backward Class]] by the governments of both Andra Pradesh, Telangana and India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aponline.gov.in/Quick%20Links/Departments/Backward%20Classes%20Welfare/A%20P%20Backward%20Classes%20Co-operative%20Finance%20Corporation/FAQ/FAQ.html |title=Frequently Asked Questions|website=aponline.gov.in|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref>\n* In [[Tamilnadu]], The Kona Gollas are classified as a [[Forward class]] by The Government of Tamilnadu.\n* The Tottiyans of Tamilnadu are Classified under [[Most Backward Class]] and also under [[List of denotified communities of Tamil Nadu|DNC/DNT]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.natboard.edu.in/pdoof/pbnotice2018/cns/Caste%20List%20of%20MBC%20and%20DC%20of%20Tamilnadu%20State.pdf|title=Tamilnadu Backward, Most Backward Class and DNC list|last=|first=|date=|website=Tamilnadu Government|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* In [[Karnataka]], The Kadu Gollas are classified under [[Scheduled Tribes|Other Backward class]]<nowiki/> by The Government of Karnataka.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rdpr.kar.nic.in/document/3.LIST_OF_SC&ST.pdf|title=Government of Karnataka Scheduled Castes and Tribes List|last=|first=|date=|website=Karnataka Government|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Titles used by Gollas==\n* [[Naidu]]\n* [[Nayakars|Nayakar]]\n* [[Nair]]\n* [[Pillai (Kerala title)|Pillai]]\n* [[Gowda (surname)|Gowda]]\n* [[Nayak (title)|Naik]]\n* [[Rayudu]]\n* [[Reddy (surname)|Reddy]]\n\n== Notable people==\n\n*[[Krishnadevaraya|Sri Krishnadevaraya]]<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.501532|title=Annual Report Of The Mysore Archaeological Department, For The Year 1930|first=M.H.|last=Krishna|date=1934|language=english}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Sircar|first=Dineschandra|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=-O18xhA_BXUC&pg=PA142&lpg=PA142&dq=amuktamalyada+yadava&source=bl&ots=1j4tE7M5ZT&sig=ACfU3U3ZzDgDbl2H8pvxJmiyC2Z4DCs1OA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwisiqKO_sPnAhUHzzgGHZPpAhQQ6AEwDHoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=amuktamalyada%20yadava&f=false|title=Some Epigraphical Records of the Medieval Period from Eastern India|date=1979|publisher=Abhinav Publications|isbn=978-81-7017-096-9|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Suresh|first=K. M.|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=r7xmluMu-FsC&dq=tuluva+yadava&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=yadava|title=Sculptural Art of Hampi|date=1998|publisher=Directorate of Archaeology and Museums, Mysore|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Viswanatha Nayak]]<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[Tirumala Nayaka]]<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/KavalKottam|title=Kaval Kottam}}</ref>\n* [[Kumara Kampana]]<ref name=\"Jackson2005\" />\n* [[Veerapandiya Kattabomman]]<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[Harihara I|Harihara]]<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=V5khtVz0yIgC&pg=PA9&lpg=PA9&dq=harihara+bukka+golla|title=Cyclic Tables of Hindu and Mahomedan Chronology, Regarding the History of the Telugu and Kannadi Countries to which are Added the Genealogies of Particular Hindu Families, with Essays on Various Matters of Enquiry|last=Brown|first=Charles Philip|date=1994|publisher=Asian Educational Services|isbn=978-81-206-0929-7|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Bukka Raya I|Bukka Raya]]<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Golla Dynasties==\n\n*[[Seuna (Yadava) dynasty]]<ref name=\":2\" />\n*[[Vijayanagara Empire|Vijayanagar Empire]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=IS1uAAAAMAAJ|title=Vijayanagar: As Seen by Domingos Paes and Fernao Nuniz (16th Century Portuguese Chroniclers and Others)|last=Sewell|first=Robert|date=1999|publisher=National Book Trust, India|isbn=978-81-237-2658-8|language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Madurai Nayak dynasty|Mudurai Nayak dynasty]]<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n*[[Pagonde Poligars]]<ref>{{cite thesis |last1=Prasanna |year=2017 |title=Pagonde poligars a comprehensive study |hdl=10603/228243 }}</ref>\n\n==Related Castes==\n\n* [[Kamma (caste)|Kamma]]\n\tIn the Book \u201cThe Madura country a Manual\u201d by J.H.Nelson noted that [[Kamma (caste)|Kammas]] are The Sub-division of Tottiyan (Golla) That we can see through his words given below. {{cquote| THE KAMMAVANS are a subdivision of the Tottiyan. Iam not aware in what respects they differ in origin and charecteristics from the ordinary Tottiyan. The difference is probably very trifling.|||J.H.Nelson '''<ref>{{Cite book| title=The Madura country a Manual | volume=|first=J.H| last=Nelson| authorlink= J.H.Nelson|year=1989| page=207 | publisher=Asian Educational Services| isbn=0-299-06740-8| url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.172487/page/n207}}</ref>}}\n\n* [[Balija]]\nIn the Book  \"Court and State in Nayaka Period Tamilnadu\" by Velcheru Narayana Rao defines as below\n {{cquote| These left-[[Shudra|Sudra]] groups \u2014 often referred to by the cover-title 'Balija', but also including [[Boyar caste|Boyas]], left-hand Gollas, [[Gavara]]s, and others - were first mobilized by [[Krishnadevaraya]] in the Vijayanagara heyday...These Balija fighters are not afraid of kings: some stories speak of their killing kings who interfered with their affairs.|||Velcheru Narayana Rao <ref>{{citation |last1=Rao |first1=Velcheru Narayana |last2=Shulman |first2=David Dean |first3=Sanjay |last3=Subrahmanyam |title=Symbols of Substance: Court and state in N\u0101yaka Period Tamilnadu |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=znFuAAAAMAAJ|year=1992 |publisher=Oxford University Press|page=74}}</ref>}}\n\n* [[Kapu (caste)|Kapu]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Tottiyan (Golla).jpg|Warriors Stone of Tottiyan\nFile:Ettaiyapuram raja.jpg|[[Ettayapuram]] zamindar\nFile:Kattabomman Fort.jpg|[[Veerapandiya Kattabomman]] Memorial Fort\nFile:Nayakkar Mahal Madurai.jpg|Madurai [[Thirumalai Nayakkar Palace]]\nFile:Veerapandiya Kattabomman 1999 stamp of India.jpg|[[Veerapandiya Kattabomman]]'s Postal stamp launched by The Government of [[India]] for his Sacrifice.\nFile:Purandar Fort 02.JPG|Vajragad ([[Purandar fort]]) which was Constructed by The Gollas  \n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |title=Global Encyclopaedia of the South Indian Dalit's Ethnography|volume= 1|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Global_Encyclopaedia_of_the_South_Indian.html?id=Xcpa_T-7oVQC |first=Nagendra Kr |l