a}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n\n{{infobox caste\n| caste_name             = Golla\n| classification         =\n| country                = {{unbulleted list\n | [[India]]\n }}\n| region                 = {{unbulleted list\n | [[Andhra Pradesh]]\n | [[Telangana]]\n | [[Tamil Nadu]]\n | [[Karnataka]]\n }}\n| languages              ={{unbulleted list\n | [[Telugu language|Telugu]] , [[Kannada]], [[Tulu language|Tulu]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n }}\n| religions              = [[Image:AUM symbol, the primary (highest) name of the God as per the Vedas.svg|15px]] [[Hinduism]] \n| ethnicity               =\n[[Aryans]] }}\n\n'''Golla''':-  Golla Naidu (or) Nayakkars are known as Telugu-speaking [[Yadava]]s in the [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Telangana]], [[Tamil Nadu|Tamilnadu]], [[Karnataka]] castes list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Writereaddata/cl/karnataka.pdf|title=CENTRAL LIST OF OBCs FOR THE STATE OF KARNATAKA|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bcmbcmw.tn.gov.in/obc/faq/andhrapradesh.pdf|title=CENTRAL LIST OF OBCs FOR THE STATE OF ANDHRA PRADESH|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  According to the document, there were 15,38,031 people in India based on the population census taken in 1911.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dspace.gipe.ac.in/xmlui/bitstream/handle/10973/18956/GIPE-016854.pdf?sequence=3&isAllowed=y|title=India Caste Census 1911|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> According to the current census of Andhra Pradesh Gollas contributes 7% of the population in the state and also Gollas are the dominant community in the districts of [[West Godavari]] and [[Cuddapah]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/rice-bowl-voters-may-tilt-the-scales/article27580287.ece|title='Rice bowl' voters may tilt the scales|last=W.chandrakanth|date=2004-03-23|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-01-02|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/71028/13/13_chapter%25207.pdf|title=Political Ecology|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nGollas are a group of the Nayakkar traditions who were migrated from Andhra Pradesh to Tamil Nadu, Karnataka, etc. They are commonly known as [[Naidu]] or Naicker.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite journal|date=September 1910|title=The Castes and Tribes of Southern India 1|journal=Nature|volume=84|issue=2134|pages=365\u2013367|doi=10.1038/084365a0|issn=0028-0836|bibcode=1910Natur..84..365.|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/8e35f3ed6744e9eecce4420277908f2f40e217ef}}</ref> They are also called \"[[Vatuka|Vadukar]]\" <ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.172487|title=The Madura Country A Manual I To V|last=G.h.nelson|date=1989}}</ref> in Tamil because, they came from the north of Tamil Nadu and also known as [[Rajakambalam Nayakar|Rajakambalatar]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.m.wikisource.org/wiki/Castes_and_Tribes_of_Southern_India/Tottiyan|title=Castes and Tribes of Southern India/Tottiyan - Wikisource, the free online library|website=en.m.wikisource.org|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> in Tamil Nadu. The word Kambalattar is derived from two major reasons they are:- \n* \"Kambalathar\" is from the word of [[Kampili kingdom|Kampili]] (Bellary). Gollas who came from [[Kampili kingdom|Kampili region]] (Bellary) are known as Kambalathar.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Singh|first=Kumar Suresh|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=YBEwAQAAIAAJ&q=kambalattar&dq=kambalattar&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjCsqv56sPnAhXFpOkKHcQyBCAQ6AEIUjAG|title=People of India|last2=India|first2=Anthropological Survey of|date=2001|publisher=Anthropological Survey of India|isbn=978-81-85938-88-2|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Singh|first=Kumar Suresh|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=1lZuAAAAMAAJ&dq=India's+Communities+madurai+nayaka&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=+madurai+nayaka|title=India's Communities|date=1998|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-563354-2|language=en}}</ref>\n* The Word \"Kambal\" meaning ''blanket'' and referred to three endogamous divisions namely, Vekkili, Thokala and Yerrakolla.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Ramesh|first=K. V.|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Svasti_%C5%9Ar%C4%AB.html?id=bAaFAAAAIAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Svasti \u015ar\u012b: Dr. B.Ch. Chhabra felicitation volume|last2=Prasad|first2=Agam|last3=Tewari|first3=S. P.|date=1984|publisher=Agam|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Ethnicity of the Golla Community==\n\n===Gollas were Aryans===\n* In the Book \" Bharata Desada Kurubar Charitre\" by [[V. R. Hanumanthaiah]] stated that {{cquote| The Shepherds belonged to the [[Aryan]] race. While making his thesis statement, he had referred to the various references to the shepherds in the Vedic literature. According to his study, the primary occupations of the Aryans were [[animal husbandry]] and weaving blankets, besides [[agriculture]]. He goes on to state that the shepherds were variously called as Avipal, Ajapal, Meshapal, Gopal during the [[Vedic period]] and that these people are at present known across the country with a variety of names |||V.R.Hanumanthaiah <ref>{{citation |first=V. R|last=Hanumanthaiah  |title=Bharata Deshada Kurbar Charitre  |year=1942|publisher=Karnatak Kurbar Sangha Publication|page=46}}</ref>}}\n* In The Book \" Karnataka Veera Kshatriyaru \" by [[S. B. Joshi]] states that the shepherds were descendants of the [[Aryans]]. He further states that{{cquote| The Term Kambali (blanket) has been recognised in the Vedic literature. Besides, he states that there are slokas in the [[Rig Veda]] that were recited by the Gollas while praying \u2018Pushan\u2019 (Sun) venerating him as the protector of their sheep. The following is the verse quoted in this context:-'''Where the grass is green and abundant,Where the grass appears beautiful In that blissful site let our sheep Thrive, and afford us good pasture,And such lands, and give us the strength in battles.20'''.  The above references provide evidences that there was a community of [[shepherds]] among the Aryans. The scholars referred above have, therefore, declared that the present day shepherds be treated as the descendants of the Aryan race. The argument that the shepherds belonged to the [[Aryan]] race was not a recent phenomenon, but is based on the premise that there existed communities that reared animals even during the Vedic period|||S.B.Joshi <ref>{{citation |first=Joshi|last=S.B  |title=Karnataka Veera Kshatriyaru (in Kannada)|publisher=Mysore Government Press|page=17}}</ref>}}\n\n==Origin of the caste ==\n[[File:Krishna in Brindavana.jpg|thumb|200px|Lord Sri Krishna]]\n* ''The'' ''Golla'' and their tribes claims to be the descendants of [[Yayati]] king of the [[Mahabharata]]. Yayati king had six sons. The last of them was a son of Kariyawala. His name is Avulu Amrithamaya. He had sons named Oli Raju and Simhadri Raju. The descendants of this tradition are Bedha Raju, Erunuka Raju, Nalunuka Raju and Polla Raju. The Golla people claim themselves as the descendants of these kings in the Mahabharata. Further, they are the Ahir (pastoral) descendants of [[Krishna|Sri Krishna]]. The Ahirs were belonged, and thus were members of the  \"''[[Kshatriya]]''\" (warrior) class in the Hindu ''[[Varna]]'' system.<ref name=\"Pandey2005\">{{cite book|author=Aditya Pandey|title=South Asia: Politics of South Asia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LaINywMCwgAC&pg=PA181|year=2005|publisher=Gyan Publishing House|isbn=978-81-8205-303-8|pages=181\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.m.wikisource.org/wiki/Castes_and_Tribes_of_Southern_India/Golla|title=Castes and Tribes of Southern India/Golla - Wikisource, the free online library|website=en.m.wikisource.org|access-date=2019-12-24}}</ref>\n* In the third volume of their book \u201cCastes and Tribes of Central Provinces\u201d, R.V. Russel and Hiralal give a different version as to the origins of Gollas. They state that [[Shiva|Lord Mahadeva]] had created the Gollas to take care of his sheep. Hence the shepherds among the Gollas consider him as the progenitor of their clan.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.211521|title=The Tribes And Castes Of The Central Provinces Of India Vol-iii|last=Russell R. V.|date=1916}}</ref>\n* Nanjundayya & Ananthakrishna Iyer states that the Gollas are the descendants of the progeny of a [[Brahmin]] woman and a [[Kshatriya]] man. They lived in Brindavan, rearing animals and eking their livelihood by selling dairy products. Since Lord Sri Krishna spent his childhood among the Gollas, it is said that the [[Yadava]] clan of Sri Krishna is of the same community. It is also stated that they lived in Repalle village at the beginning of [[Kali Yuga|Kali Yug]]. During the reign of Rajaraja Narendra, it was said that they immigrated to southern regions from Repalle. It is because of the above inferences, the Gollas consider themselves to belong to the Yadava clan or Golla kings. The very term Golla kings asserts their kinship with [[Krishna|Sri Krishna]], besides asserting them to be of a higher stratum of the society. Nanjundayya and Ananthakrishna Iyer refer to the last inference in the third volume of their book \u201cThe Mysore Tribes & Castes\u201d.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.22885|title=The Mysore Tribes And Castes Vol. 3|last=Iyer|first=L. K. Ananthakrishna|date=1930}}</ref>\n\n==Sub-Castes of Golla==\n{{OSM Location map\n| coord = {{coord|15.0950|N|76.5488|E}}   <!-- Map center -->\n| float = right\n| zoom = 8\n| width = 300 <!-- width and height of the frame. numeric input - do not add px -->\n| height = 270\n| caption = <center>Kampili Nadu Region</center>\n| minimap = \n| mini-fi